('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:4ee00a97', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "Changes in the price index affect consumption and investment decisions. Which one of the following statements is true?", "options": ["The economy experienced inflation in every year", "The highest rate of inflation was in 2016", "The lowest rate of inflation was in 2014", "The price level was highest at the end of 2015"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:420px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Year</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2013</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2014</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2015</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2016</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Price index</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">100</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">106</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">120</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">122</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "The INDEX rises every year, so prices rose every year. Then check the rates: 2014 is +6%, 2015 is +13.2%, 2016 is only +1.7%.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2) · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — The economy experienced inflation in every year</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The index rises every year (100→106→120→122), so there was inflation each year. The highest RATE was 2015 (+13.2%), not 2016; the lowest was 2016 (+1.7%), not 2014 (+6%); and the price level was highest at the end of 2016 (122), not 2015.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:cf632ddf', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "Inflation can be measured using the", "options": ["consumer price index", "customer price index", "consumer price interest", "customer price interest"], "hint": "CPI — get all three words right. It is about CONSUMERS and it is an INDEX.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — consumer price index</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPI = Consumer Price Index. Not \"customer\", and not \"interest\" — the distractors change one word each.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:0b53fb02', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "A nominal value is one which", "options": ["has been adjusted for inflation", "has been adjusted for taxation", "has not been adjusted for inflation", "has not been adjusted for taxation"], "hint": "Nominal = the raw money figure. REAL is the one that has been adjusted for inflation.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — has not been adjusted for inflation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nominal values are in money terms, unadjusted. REAL values are the ones adjusted for inflation. Tax is irrelevant to the distinction.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:96b65bac', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "How might an increase in interest rates affect the economy?", "options": ["Decrease unemployment", "Improve price stability", "Increase economic growth", "Increase inflation"], "hint": "Higher interest rates reduce borrowing and spending, so demand falls. What does that do to the rate of price rises?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Improve price stability</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher rates cut borrowing and total spending, easing demand-pull inflation and bringing prices nearer the target — improving price stability. They would tend to RAISE unemployment and REDUCE growth.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates identified the correct answer (B).</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:e8490fbb', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "What is a definition of price stability?", "options": ["A sustained rise in the general price level", "GDP per capita increases gradually", "Inflation remains constant", "Prices increase at an acceptable low rate"], "hint": "Careful with ''inflation remains constant'' — inflation could be constant at 20% a year, which is not stable prices at all.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Prices increase at an acceptable low rate</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Price stability means prices rise slowly and predictably, around the 2% target. Option A defines INFLATION itself.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion correctly identified D; however a common misconception was ''C'', which is incorrect because inflation could be CONSTANT at a very high rate and thus not stable prices.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:72cdc8b5', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "The UK uses CPI to measure inflation. Which statement about CPI is correct?", "options": ["It does not include the prices of exports", "It measures the prices of all goods and services in the UK", "It only measures the prices of goods", "The letters CPI stand for customer price index"], "hint": "CPI measures what UK CONSUMERS buy. Exports are bought by foreigners, so they''re excluded. It''s also a sample basket, not everything.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — It does not include the prices of exports</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPI tracks what UK consumers buy, so exports are excluded. It measures a representative BASKET, not all goods and services (B); it includes services as well as goods (C); and CPI is the CONSUMER price index (D).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A pleasing number answered correctly, however a significant number of candidates answered D.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:7c752b83', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "In which two countries did the general price level DECREASE between 2021 and 2022?", "options": ["Countries S and V", "Countries T and W", "Countries T and Z", "Countries W and Z"], "caseStudy": "<p>The table shows the rate of inflation for 2021 and 2022 in five countries.</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:400px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\"></th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2021 (%)</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">2022 (%)</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Country S</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">4.7</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">4.1</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Country T</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">–2.4</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">–0.5</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Country V</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">12.3</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">3.1</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Country W</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">8.1</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">0.3</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Country Z</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">8.1</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">–0.1</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Prices only FALL when the inflation rate is NEGATIVE. A rate that drops from 8.1% to 0.3% still means prices ROSE, just slowly.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2) · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Countries T and Z</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Only a NEGATIVE rate means the price level fell in 2022: T (–0.5%) and Z (–0.1%). Country W''s rate fell from 8.1% to 0.3%, but 0.3% is still positive, so its prices ROSE — just much more slowly.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion answered C correctly. It is worth preparing candidates on the implications of ABSOLUTE CHANGES and RATES OF CHANGE.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:7866727f', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "If a group of workers was awarded a 10% pay rise, but their productivity had increased by 6%, then the most likely result would be", "options": ["a fall in consumer confidence", "a fall in government tax revenue", "an increase in consumer debt", "an increase in cost-push inflation"], "hint": "Pay is rising faster than output per worker, so the labour cost of each unit produced goes UP. What kind of inflation does rising costs cause?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — an increase in cost-push inflation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wages rise 10% while productivity rises only 6%, so the cost of producing each unit rises. Firms pass the higher costs on as higher prices — cost-push inflation.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:be86933b', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is used to measure inflation. Which statement about CPI is NOT correct?", "options": ["It is measured every month", "It measures what an average family spends money on", "It only measures the price of goods", "It uses a system of weighting"], "hint": "Read the emboldened NOT. Three statements are true of CPI — which one is false? Think about whether CPI covers haircuts and bus fares.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — It only measures the price of goods</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPI covers goods AND services, so C is the false statement. It IS measured monthly, it IS based on an average family''s spending, and it DOES use weighting.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The emboldened word ''not'' indicates that only C can be correct (the others are all true).</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:22544182', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "What was the average monthly mobile phone contract at the end of 2022?", "options": ["£46.80", "£47.25", "£49.05", "£49.14"], "caseStudy": "<p>In 2021 the average monthly mobile phone contract was £45. The rate of inflation was 4% in 2021 and 5% in 2022.</p>", "hint": "Two steps, applied one after the other — not 9% in one go. Add 4% first, then add 5% to THAT new figure.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2) · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — £49.14</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>£45 + 4% = £46.80; £46.80 + 5% = £49.14. Adding 9% in one step gives £49.05 (option C) — the trap, because the second year''s inflation applies to the already-inflated price.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion correctly answered D. This required candidates completing TWO steps of calculation (adding 4% to £45 and then a further 5%), i.e. £45 + 4% = £46.80; £46.80 + 5% = £49.14.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:6331b2fe', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "A period of price stability is most likely if", "options": ["prices increase at an acceptably low rate", "real values decrease as nominal values increase", "the rate of inflation is negative", "there is a fair distribution of income"], "hint": "Price stability is about the RATE of price rises being low and predictable — not about fairness, and not about prices falling.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — prices increase at an acceptably low rate</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Negative inflation (deflation) is not price stability either — it brings its own problems. Fair income distribution is a different macroeconomic objective entirely.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion correctly answered A, although a common error was to confuse price stability and EQUALITY (giving the incorrect answer D).</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:244650ed', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "What effect will this have on producers?", "options": ["An increase in consumer confidence", "An increase in menu costs", "An increase in shoe leather costs", "An increase in the purchasing power of money"], "caseStudy": "<p>The UK''s rate of inflation is forecast by some experts to reach 7% during 2023.</p>", "hint": "The question asks about PRODUCERS. Menu costs are the cost to a FIRM of reprinting price lists; shoe leather costs fall on buyers searching for prices.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — An increase in menu costs</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Menu costs are borne by PRODUCERS, who must keep changing their price lists as inflation pushes prices up. Shoe leather costs (C) fall on buyers, and inflation REDUCES the purchasing power of money (D).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Although a significant proportion correctly answered B (a clear cost on a producer), several answered ''C'' (a cost on a buyer/consumer) or ''D'' (which is the OPPOSITE of the effect of inflation on purchasing power).</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:696a4906', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q15", "question": "It can be seen from the diagram that the country experienced inflation", "options": ["in every year", "only from Year 3 onwards", "only until Year 3", "that was negative up to Year 3 and positive afterwards"], "caseStudy": "<p>The diagram shows some information on annual changes in the price level for a country.</p>\n<img src=\"/images/economics/3-4-price-level-change-diagram-extracted.png\" alt=\"Diagram from the OCR exam paper showing the rate of change in price level on the vertical axis against time on the horizontal axis. The curve starts high at Year 0, falls to a minimum at Year 3, then rises again — but it stays ABOVE the horizontal axis throughout, so the rate of change is positive in every year\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:480px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "The axis is the RATE OF CHANGE in the price level. The curve dips but never crosses below the horizontal axis — so the rate stays positive the whole time.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — in every year</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The curve stays ABOVE the horizontal axis throughout, so the rate of change in the price level is positive every year — meaning inflation every year. The dip to Year 3 is inflation SLOWING, not prices falling. Only a curve going below the axis would show deflation.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:18153e7f', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16", "question": "Which of the following items is included in the calculation of the UK''s Consumer Price Index (CPI)?", "options": ["Government spending on education", "The price of children''s clothes", "The price of a machine bought by a company", "The price of exports"], "hint": "CPI measures what a typical HOUSEHOLD buys. Government spending, firms'' machinery and exports are all bought by someone other than UK consumers.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — The price of children''s clothes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPI tracks the basket bought by typical UK consumers, so children''s clothes are in it. Government spending, capital machinery bought by firms, and exports (bought by foreigners) are all excluded.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:190e6253', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q17", "question": "Which of the following is a consequence of inflation for consumers?", "options": ["Fall in tax revenue", "Increase in menu costs", "Real incomes may fall", "Savings increase in value"], "hint": "The question is about CONSUMERS. Menu costs hit producers, tax revenue is the government''s concern — and inflation reduces, not increases, the real value of savings.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Real incomes may fall</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If prices rise faster than wages, consumers'' real incomes — what their pay can actually buy — fall. Menu costs fall on producers, tax revenue on government, and inflation REDUCES the real value of savings.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:6797cc12', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q18", "question": "Under which of the following circumstances would it be best to be a lender?", "options": ["The nominal rate of interest is 0 percent and the inflation rate is 0 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 2 percent and the inflation rate is 5 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 5 percent and the inflation rate is 1 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 7 percent and the inflation rate is 4 percent"], "hint": "A lender wants the highest REAL return. Work out nominal minus inflation for each option and pick the biggest.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — nominal 5%, inflation 1%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Real rate = nominal − inflation. A: 0 − 0 = 0%. B: 2 − 5 = −3%. C: 5 − 1 = <strong>+4%</strong>. D: 7 − 4 = +3%. The lender gains most in C, even though D has the higher nominal rate — the trap.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:45b41b31', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "Data is often presented in terms of nominal or real figures. The difference between them takes into account", "options": ["direct taxes", "the rate of inflation", "the rate of interest", "wider supply-side policy"], "hint": "Real = nominal adjusted for one thing only.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — the rate of inflation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Real values are nominal values adjusted for inflation, so they show purchasing power rather than the raw money amount.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:4fa41bed', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q20", "question": "How does the consumer price index measure the rate of inflation?", "options": ["By using changes in the rate of growth of the money supply", "By using the increase in the annual GDP per capita figures", "Through a process of weighing a range of goods and services", "Through a survey of prices in a typical basket of goods and services"], "hint": "Careful with C — CPI does use WEIGHTING, but weighting alone isn''t how it measures inflation. What is actually surveyed each month?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Through a survey of prices in a typical basket of goods and services</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>CPI surveys the prices of a representative basket each month. Weighting (C) is applied to that basket to reflect how much households spend on each item, but the measurement itself is the price survey.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:71c0d569', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q21", "question": "Which of the statements is correct? Prices", "options": ["fell from 2016 to 2019 and then increased", "rose only in 2020", "rose throughout the period shown", "were constant in 2017–2018"], "caseStudy": "<p>The table shows the rate of inflation for Country A for 2016–2020.</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:340px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Year</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Inflation rate %</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2016</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">3.0</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2017</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2.0</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2018</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2.0</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2019</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">1.5</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2020</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2.5</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Every figure is POSITIVE, so prices rose every year. A falling rate (3.0 → 1.5) means prices rose more slowly, not that they fell. And 2.0 twice means prices rose by 2% in BOTH years — not that they stayed constant.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — rose throughout the period shown</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>All five rates are positive, so prices rose every year. Option A confuses a FALLING RATE with falling prices; option D confuses a constant RATE (2.0% in both 2017 and 2018) with constant prices — prices actually rose 2% in each of those years.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-4-price-stability:exam:33cba987', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q23", "question": "If the rate of inflation is decreasing, but still positive, the price level will:", "options": ["fall", "rise", "stay the same", "become negative"], "hint": "This is the single most important distinction in the topic. A positive rate — however small, however much it is shrinking — still means prices are going UP.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — rise</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A positive inflation rate means prices are still rising. A DECREASING but positive rate means they are rising more slowly than before — but the price level still goes up. Only a negative rate makes the price level fall.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb)
